Q: Run the model below and then inspect the posterior distribution and explain what it is accomplishing.

\(\verb+mp <- map2stan(+\)
\(\verb+ alist(+\)
\(\verb+ a ~ dnorm(0,1),+\)
\(\verb+ b ~ dcauchy(0,1)+\)
\(\verb+ ),+\)
\(\verb+ data=list(y=1),+\)
\(\verb+ start=list(a=0,b=0),+\)
\(\verb+ iter=1e4, warmup=100, WAIC=FALSE+\)
\(\verb+)+\)

Inspecting the code above, we can first see that a likelihood has not been defined. In fact, we have only defined prior distributions for two parameters a and b, where:

a follows a standard Normal distribution (\(\mu = 0\), \(\sigma = 1\))
b follows a standard Cauchy distribution (\(x_{0} = 0\), \(\gamma = 1\))

Second, we define a dataframe with one element, y=1.

Third, we specify a starting point of zero for each parameter. This gives the computer a rough location of the estimates.

Finally, we know that Markov Chains approximate using iterative sampling. Convince youself that \(\verb+iter = 1e4+\) and \(\verb+warmup = 100+\) are sufficient.

Q: Compare the samples for the parameters a and b. Can you explain the different trace plots, using what you know about the Cauchy distribution?

Since there is no likelihood, we actually sample from a posterior distribution which is just composed of the priors.

precis(mp)
##    Mean StdDev lower 0.89 upper 0.89 n_eff Rhat
## a  0.01   0.99      -1.56       1.60  9900    1
## b -2.65  60.97      -6.31       6.16   567    1

Comparing the \(\verb+n_eff+\) values, the effective sample size for b is much smaller than that of a. Recall that ideally,

\[\verb+n_eff+ \approx \verb+iter+-\verb+warmup+\] \[\verb+n_eff+ \approx 9900\]

So, we speculate if the chain for b is inefficient. Checking the trace plots may give us a better idea of what happened:

A difference between the two plots is immediately obvious:

The trace plot for a (left) is what we typically expect from a Gaussian parameter: stationary and well-mixing. The trace plot for b (right) shows that occasionally a large estimate of the parameter value is drawn.

Recall the shape of the standard Cauchy distribution (red) compared to the standard normal (black):

p<-seq(-10,10,by=0.1)
plot(p, dnorm(p, mean = 0, sd = 1),type="l")
lines(p, dcauchy(p, location = 0, scale = 1), col="red")

See that the Cauchy distribution has heavier tails that do not converge to zero as \(n\to\infty\) (this is why the Cauchy distribution has undefined mean and variance). This explains the occasional spikes in the trace plot, representing the path taken by the Markov Chain when a sample estimate is drawn from way out in the tails.

More clearly, see below the resemblance between randomly generated points from each distribution with sample size \(\approx \verb+n_eff+\) and the trace plots for each respective parameter.

a = rnorm(9000, mean = 0, sd = 1)
b = rcauchy(1000, location = 0, scale = 1)

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(a, type = "p", col = rgb(red = 0, green = 0.5, blue = 1, alpha = 0.2), 
     pch = 16, cex = 0.5, main = "a = rnorm(1e4, mean = 0, sd = 1)", ylim = c(-5,5))
plot(b, type = "p", col = rgb(red = 0, green = 0.5, blue = 1, alpha = 0.2),
     pch = 16, cex = 0.5, main = "b = rcauchy(1e4, location = 0, scale = 1)", ylim = c(-300,500))
